        introduction: "The Mont-Saint-Michel to Paris journey is one of France's great tourist classics, linking the Wonder of the Western World to the City of Light across 360 km of soothing Norman landscapes. Mont-Saint-Michel, a UNESCO World Heritage Site visited by 2.5 million people annually, is often the starting or ending point of a Parisian stay for international tourists. The Benedictine abbey, founded in 708 by Bishop Aubert of Avranches following an apparition of the Archangel Michael, rises 80 metres above the sand flats and represents one of the most astonishing architectural feats of the Middle Ages. The bay surrounding it, with Europe's highest tides, is a unique Ramsar-classified ecosystem. The taxi journey then crosses the Norman bocage — land of cider, Camembert and Calvados — passes through Caen, city of William the Conqueror, then follows the Seine valley along the Normandy motorway, one of France's most scenic with views of the river's meanders, chalk cliffs and green hillsides. The long-distance taxi is particularly popular with international families and groups wanting a direct door-to-door transfer between the Mont and their Paris hotel, avoiding the complexities of trains (shuttle to Pontorson, TER, then TGV with connections). It is also ideal for travellers with bulky luggage, reduced mobility, or those wishing to make tourist stops along the way.",
